4
00:00:22,470 --> 00:00:24,062
This is one With the Wind
for television.

5
00:00:24,230 --> 00:00:26,266
l didn't have to create Madeline.

6
00:00:26,430 --> 00:00:28,705
John Jakes created Madeline.

7
00:00:29,150 --> 00:00:33,143
The popularity of the American Çivil War
and all that goes with it...

8
00:00:33,310 --> 00:00:39,180
... really lies
in the emotion of people...

9
00:00:39,350 --> 00:00:43,138
... who are close to one another
being torn apart by what they believe...

10
00:00:43,310 --> 00:00:44,868
... or what they're supposed
to believe.

11
00:00:45,030 --> 00:00:49,387
Roots was the story of the South
from the black point of view.

12
00:00:49,550 --> 00:00:51,427
North and South is the story
of the South...

13
00:00:51,590 --> 00:00:52,864
... from the white point of view.

14
00:00:53,030 --> 00:00:56,909
The very first thing that you hear
when the project goes on...

15
00:00:57,070 --> 00:00:59,868
... is the main title and the music.

16
00:01:00,030 --> 00:01:02,066
And the music is gonna carry
that message...

17
00:01:02,230 --> 00:01:03,743
... of what is this thing all about.

18
00:01:04,430 --> 00:01:05,545
Çue marker.

19
00:01:25,390 --> 00:01:27,745
Well, North and South,
the trilogy began...

20
00:01:29,070 --> 00:01:31,186
... with a three-book contract
that l had.

21
00:01:31,350 --> 00:01:34,228
Originally, it was to be three books...

22
00:01:35,550 --> 00:01:38,747
... about a military family
through the years, one family.

23
00:01:39,230 --> 00:01:41,186
l then started to research it.

24
00:01:41,350 --> 00:01:44,660
And of course, the first place l went to
was West Point.

25
00:01:44,830 --> 00:01:46,946
Read the history of West Point.

26
00:01:47,110 --> 00:01:51,228
And in one book,
l came across this one page...

27
00:01:51,390 --> 00:01:55,861
... that named all of the generals
who fought each other...

28
00:01:56,030 --> 00:01:58,828
... in the Çivil War on opposite sides.

29
00:01:58,990 --> 00:02:00,946
They had all known each other
at West Point.

30
00:02:01,110 --> 00:02:02,384
They had gone to school together.

31
00:02:02,550 --> 00:02:05,223
They had gone to Mexico together,
fought there.

32
00:02:05,390 --> 00:02:09,065
And l called up my editor
and l said, ''Julian, this has gotta be it.

33
00:02:09,230 --> 00:02:12,461
Now, we're gonna do two families
at West Point...

34
00:02:12,630 --> 00:02:15,542
... and it divides very nicely
into North and South...

35
00:02:15,710 --> 00:02:17,666
... dealing with the antebellum years...

36
00:02:17,830 --> 00:02:20,628
... Love and War dealing
with the war itself...

37
00:02:20,790 --> 00:02:22,667
... Heaven and Hell dealing
with Reconstruction. ''

38
00:02:22,830 --> 00:02:24,582
And that was it,
but it was an evolution.

39
00:02:24,750 --> 00:02:27,105
Well, the North and South
came about...

40
00:02:27,270 --> 00:02:29,500
... because l actually got a call
from ABÇ...

41
00:02:29,670 --> 00:02:32,104
... they just bought a book
called North and South.

42
00:02:32,270 --> 00:02:33,669
l had just done Roots.

43
00:02:34,990 --> 00:02:36,582
l did The Thorn Birds for them,
they said:

44
00:02:36,750 --> 00:02:38,263
''We couldn't think
of anybody better...

45
00:02:38,430 --> 00:02:40,785
... we'd like to turn over
the whole project but to you. ''

46
00:02:40,950 --> 00:02:43,669
So l read the book, the first book,
right away.

47
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:45,502
l said it's a great, juicy story.

48
00:02:45,670 --> 00:02:48,423
John Jakes is a very juicy writer.

49
00:02:48,630 --> 00:02:53,784
lt was material that could be adapted
so well for the form, the long form...

50
00:02:55,110 --> 00:02:57,578
... in which feature films can't do...

51
00:02:57,750 --> 00:03:01,663
... because they're compressed
into an hour and a half or two hours.

52
00:03:02,110 --> 00:03:06,342
And this story needed a lot of time
to be told.

53
00:03:06,510 --> 00:03:08,546
To be told effectively
and to be told the right way.

54
00:03:08,710 --> 00:03:13,261
l knew l had to do a formidable amount
of research for the trilogy.

55
00:03:13,430 --> 00:03:18,345
First of all, because the Çivil War
is such an enormously popular subject...

56
00:03:18,510 --> 00:03:21,149
... not only in the United States,
but around the world.

57
00:03:21,310 --> 00:03:26,259
Today, the Çivil War is called sometimes
the Brothers' War, the Çousins' War.

58
00:03:26,430 --> 00:03:31,902
And phrases like that
really exemplify the split...

59
00:03:32,070 --> 00:03:36,188
... the painful split
that took part in our country.

60
00:03:37,030 --> 00:03:39,590
y ou know, years ago...

61
00:03:39,750 --> 00:03:42,423
... John Çalhoun said
that West Point men...

62
00:03:42,590 --> 00:03:45,024
... would lead great armies.

63
00:03:49,190 --> 00:03:51,499
He never thought they'd be leading them
against each other.

64
00:03:51,670 --> 00:03:55,265
And l hadn't really realized
it was that deep or that harrowing.

65
00:03:55,430 --> 00:03:57,227
But that was the whole point
that emerged...

66
00:03:57,390 --> 00:04:00,621
... in writing North and South
was these two guys basically...

67
00:04:00,790 --> 00:04:02,906
... who had a great affection
for one another...

68
00:04:03,070 --> 00:04:06,107
... as West Point classmates.

69
00:04:06,790 --> 00:04:09,987
At the end, when war broke out,
they were pulled apart.

70
00:04:10,190 --> 00:04:11,543
They each had to go their own way.

71
00:04:11,710 --> 00:04:15,066
And it was more
than just a casual decision.

72
00:04:15,230 --> 00:04:18,825
lt was very, very emotional.

73
00:04:19,750 --> 00:04:23,379
l tell you, we didn't have any problems
with the theme...

74
00:04:23,550 --> 00:04:26,622
... with any controversy
with the North and South...

75
00:04:26,790 --> 00:04:28,667
... for one particular reason.

76
00:04:28,830 --> 00:04:31,060
y ou heard the South's point of view...

77
00:04:31,270 --> 00:04:33,784
... and you heard the North's point
of view, so it wasn't... .

78
00:04:33,950 --> 00:04:36,783
y ou heard slavery.

79
00:04:36,950 --> 00:04:39,510
But then you heard the people
in the North saying how bad it was.

80
00:04:39,910 --> 00:04:42,185
l was really intrigued
with this time period...

81
00:04:42,350 --> 00:04:47,708
... because, at the same time,
it was a coming-of-age story...

82
00:04:47,870 --> 00:04:49,906
... in many ways for Orry and George.

83
00:04:50,070 --> 00:04:53,745
lt was a coming-of-age period
in my life as Patrick, you know.

84
00:04:53,910 --> 00:04:56,788
Having to really analyze
and look at who l am...

85
00:04:58,110 --> 00:05:00,021
... and what l was about
and who l thought l was...

86
00:05:00,190 --> 00:05:01,703
... as opposed to who l really was.

87
00:05:01,910 --> 00:05:02,979
Television has its place...

88
00:05:05,230 --> 00:05:08,142
... and North and South definitely
had its place telling the story...

89
00:05:08,350 --> 00:05:13,185
... of certain aspects of slavery...

90
00:05:13,990 --> 00:05:18,745
... seen from a white man's
perspective.

91
00:05:19,390 --> 00:05:22,826
l think it did marvelous things
with Virgilia's character, you know...

92
00:05:22,990 --> 00:05:25,345
... the abolitionists and all of that.

93
00:05:25,550 --> 00:05:29,065
Reading John Jakes' books
gave me great insight...

94
00:05:29,230 --> 00:05:33,667
... but it also prodded me
to do a lot more research.

95
00:05:33,830 --> 00:05:35,866
And also delve
into my own family tree.

96
00:05:36,030 --> 00:05:38,021
Some who have died
and some who spent time...

97
00:05:38,190 --> 00:05:42,069
... in Çonfederate prison camps,
and so forth...

98
00:05:42,230 --> 00:05:47,509
... so that really brought it
very close to me.

99
00:05:47,670 --> 00:05:49,069
The only thing l determined...

100
00:05:49,230 --> 00:05:52,745
... before l started
writing North and South...

101
00:05:53,190 --> 00:05:57,388
... was that l would not be an apologist
for slavery under any circumstances.

102
00:05:57,550 --> 00:06:03,022
l've actually been cornered at parties
by what l call professional Southerners...

103
00:06:03,190 --> 00:06:07,149
... who tried to tell me that slavery
wasn't so bad.

104
00:06:07,310 --> 00:06:09,266
lt was okay.

105
00:06:09,430 --> 00:06:15,141
They were wage slaves in the North.
They were slaves in the factories.

106
00:06:16,710 --> 00:06:21,386
And to that, l always say, ''y es,
but in the North, they could walk away.

107
00:06:21,550 --> 00:06:24,189
They could just walk away. ''

108
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:35,344
l had no idea what l was getting into,
because l am a Southern man.

109
00:06:35,550 --> 00:06:41,341
l do come from a belief system
that is based in integrity and morality...

110
00:06:41,510 --> 00:06:43,421
... and a certain code.

111
00:06:43,590 --> 00:06:46,502
This time period,
with the Çivil War brewing...

112
00:06:46,670 --> 00:06:50,106
... in many ways, it was the first time
men were challenged...

113
00:06:50,270 --> 00:06:53,945
... to start questioning this code.

114
00:06:54,110 --> 00:06:55,782
l was living in South Çarolina...

115
00:06:55,950 --> 00:07:00,102
... recently moved in
at the time l started the book.

116
00:07:00,270 --> 00:07:02,943
l located their plantation
up near Çharleston.

117
00:07:03,110 --> 00:07:06,989
l debated as to whether
to put the Main family...

118
00:07:07,150 --> 00:07:10,028
... in the cotton business
or the rice business.

119
00:07:10,190 --> 00:07:13,865
Ultimately, l decided on the rice business
because that was older...

120
00:07:14,030 --> 00:07:16,180
... than the cotton business
in South Çarolina.

121
00:07:16,510 --> 00:07:22,142
l would say the Main family
were middle-of-the-road Southerners...

122
00:07:22,310 --> 00:07:24,460
... in the sense
that they were slave owners...

123
00:07:24,630 --> 00:07:27,747
... but tried not to mistreat
their slaves.

124
00:07:27,910 --> 00:07:31,141
But when push came to shove,
they were willing...

125
00:07:31,310 --> 00:07:35,986
... to apply horrible punishments
to the slaves.

126
00:07:41,430 --> 00:07:42,579
Mr. Main, sir.

127
00:07:42,790 --> 00:07:44,508
What's Priam done?
Why you beating him?

128
00:07:44,670 --> 00:07:47,946
There's no crime exactly.
lt's his attitude, sir.

129
00:07:48,110 --> 00:07:49,907
Priam don't show the proper respect.

130
00:07:50,070 --> 00:07:53,983
A good overseer knows how to get
a man's respect without beating him.

131
00:07:54,190 --> 00:07:56,340
And we don't whip slaves
at Mont Royal.

132
00:07:56,550 --> 00:07:59,622
lt really taught me what it is
to be a true Southern man, you know.

133
00:07:59,790 --> 00:08:02,304
lt was like, at one point, my agent
had a meeting with me...

134
00:08:02,470 --> 00:08:04,904
... and said, ''y ou've got to quit
calling everybody 'sir. ' ''

135
00:08:05,070 --> 00:08:06,059
l went, ''Why?''

136
00:08:06,230 --> 00:08:09,381
He says, ''Because it shows
a lack of respect for yourself. ''

137
00:08:09,550 --> 00:08:13,384
l went, ''What the hell is wrong
with you? l mean, that's insanity. ''

138
00:08:13,590 --> 00:08:15,342
lt had nothing to do
with my self-esteem.

139
00:08:15,510 --> 00:08:18,229
lt had to do with, you know,
the certain way you're brought up.

140
00:08:18,390 --> 00:08:21,462
y ou hold the door for women.
y ou pull their chair out.

141
00:08:21,630 --> 00:08:23,746
lt's your job. lt's not a macho thing.

142
00:08:23,910 --> 00:08:27,539
But also, when you say ''sir''
in a different context...

143
00:08:27,710 --> 00:08:29,826
... it can also be very dangerous,
you know.

144
00:08:29,990 --> 00:08:33,380
''Sir, you mess with me one more time,
and l break every bone in your body. ''

145
00:08:33,590 --> 00:08:35,546
Let's have you, Mr. Main.

146
00:08:37,030 --> 00:08:39,498
At your service, sir.

147
00:08:56,430 --> 00:08:59,342
We had two personalities,
we picked James Read...

148
00:08:59,510 --> 00:09:02,263
... and we had auditions and readings
and everything...

149
00:09:02,430 --> 00:09:04,022
... and James Read
looked the right to us.

150
00:09:04,190 --> 00:09:07,978
We wanted attractive-looking actors,
obviously.

151
00:09:08,430 --> 00:09:10,864
Patrick Swayze was not a big star
at the time.

152
00:09:11,030 --> 00:09:13,498
He looked perfect for us too.

153
00:09:13,710 --> 00:09:16,178
Both of them auditioned and read
and screen-tested...

154
00:09:16,350 --> 00:09:19,262
... and they got the part
because they came out the best...

155
00:09:19,430 --> 00:09:21,386
... in the screen test and the audition.

156
00:09:21,590 --> 00:09:23,342
David Wolper and l
didn't have many arguments.

157
00:09:23,510 --> 00:09:26,547
But we had one
about Orry losing his arm, you know.

158
00:09:26,710 --> 00:09:31,579
ln the book,
he loses an arm fighting in Mexico.

159
00:09:31,750 --> 00:09:36,028
Çonsequently, his other arm
is extremely powerful...

160
00:09:36,190 --> 00:09:38,181
... and it can even be used as a weapon.

161
00:09:38,350 --> 00:09:41,228
Well, David didn't wanna do that.

162
00:09:41,390 --> 00:09:43,824
And l can remember we argued about it
on the phone.

163
00:09:43,990 --> 00:09:46,629
And he finally persuaded me by saying,
''Look, '' he said.

164
00:09:46,790 --> 00:09:52,308
''lf l have to have 1 2 hours
or 1 0 hours or eight hours or whatever...

165
00:09:52,470 --> 00:09:56,429
... with Patrick Swayze with his arm
tied behind his back...

166
00:09:56,590 --> 00:09:57,705
... they won't get the story.

167
00:09:57,870 --> 00:09:59,826
They'll be saying,
'Where's his arm hiding?

168
00:09:59,990 --> 00:10:01,742
Where's his arm hiding?' ''

169
00:10:01,910 --> 00:10:04,549
So l said, ''All right, you've won.
y ou've won. ''

170
00:10:04,750 --> 00:10:07,059
Patrick has such charisma...

171
00:10:07,230 --> 00:10:12,827
... that every girl who met,
and l'm sure meets him today...

172
00:10:12,990 --> 00:10:15,220
... you meet him and you go:

173
00:10:15,390 --> 00:10:18,905
And he lights something up
inside you.

174
00:10:19,070 --> 00:10:21,823
So it wasn't difficult to act that.

175
00:10:21,990 --> 00:10:25,505
Because even though l didn't want
to sort of leap off...

176
00:10:25,710 --> 00:10:29,100
... into the sunset with him,
he's a charismatic person...

177
00:10:29,270 --> 00:10:33,229
... and he inspires those looks
and that flirtatiousness.

178
00:10:33,390 --> 00:10:35,346
l don't even know your name.

179
00:10:36,670 --> 00:10:38,865
lt's Orry, Orry Main.

180
00:10:39,030 --> 00:10:41,942
l'm from Mont Royal
just up the river.

181
00:10:43,350 --> 00:10:46,023
My name is Madeline Fabray.

182
00:10:46,230 --> 00:10:48,425
l'm delighted to meet you.

183
00:10:50,350 --> 00:10:52,659
l've always said, ''y ou give me horses,
capes and cleavage...

184
00:10:52,830 --> 00:10:54,786
... and l'm a happy man, '' you know.

185
00:10:55,870 --> 00:10:58,304
Well, l still have them.
l still have the wardrobe.

186
00:10:58,470 --> 00:11:01,428
But l've never let go
of my general's uniform...

187
00:11:01,590 --> 00:11:07,779
... and the cape when Madeline
and l make love for the first time...

188
00:11:07,950 --> 00:11:09,747
... in that burned-out church...

189
00:11:09,910 --> 00:11:13,744
... and sort of consummate
this doomed...

190
00:11:14,310 --> 00:11:18,144
... or looks like it's doomed,
relationship.

191
00:11:36,910 --> 00:11:39,299
He loved you very much.

192
00:11:39,510 --> 00:11:41,899
- l know.
- l'm gonna miss him so.

193
00:11:50,990 --> 00:11:55,268
lt was a really emotional time for me
because my dad died.

194
00:11:55,430 --> 00:11:57,819
My real dad died soon before.

195
00:11:57,990 --> 00:11:59,821
So when you asked me earlier
about, you know:

196
00:11:59,990 --> 00:12:03,380
''How does it feel
with your father dying, as Orry...

197
00:12:03,550 --> 00:12:06,064
... and having to take over the family
and that responsibility...

198
00:12:06,230 --> 00:12:08,619
... and carry on the legacy?''

199
00:12:09,150 --> 00:12:11,345
l was in the throes, personally...

200
00:12:11,510 --> 00:12:13,819
... in the throes of,
''What do l do without my dad?''

201
00:12:19,950 --> 00:12:22,987
The North
was so overwhelmingly powerful...

202
00:12:23,150 --> 00:12:28,508
... as an industrial concern,
as an industrial society...

203
00:12:28,670 --> 00:12:31,901
... that it seemed to me
that having Hazards...

204
00:12:32,070 --> 00:12:35,187
... in the iron business, making cannon,
making whatever they made...

205
00:12:35,350 --> 00:12:37,545
... during the war,
was probably a good way...

206
00:12:37,710 --> 00:12:40,508
... to exemplify the strength
of the North.

207
00:12:40,710 --> 00:12:43,224
l think that my character,
George Hazard...

208
00:12:43,390 --> 00:12:46,427
... was the conscience of the story...

209
00:12:46,590 --> 00:12:49,150
... the moral conscience,
the moral authority.

210
00:12:49,310 --> 00:12:54,384
He had a true understanding
of the division...

211
00:12:54,550 --> 00:12:59,021
... that was apparently
ripping the country apart.

212
00:12:59,190 --> 00:13:00,225
lt wasn't black and white.

213
00:13:00,390 --> 00:13:03,268
lt wasn't the South is bad,
the North is good.

214
00:13:03,430 --> 00:13:05,022
lt's much more complicated than that.

215
00:13:05,190 --> 00:13:07,260
There was not a guy
on North and South...

216
00:13:07,430 --> 00:13:09,898
... that l didn't, at one point
or another, think:

217
00:13:10,070 --> 00:13:12,584
''y ou're so darling,
you're just so darling.

218
00:13:12,750 --> 00:13:14,945
Let me just hug you and kiss you. ''

219
00:13:15,110 --> 00:13:17,180
James Read is certainly one of them.

220
00:13:17,350 --> 00:13:21,548
And of course, l do get to hug him
and kiss him in North and South III.

221
00:13:21,710 --> 00:13:24,144
A marvelous actor. He really is.

222
00:13:24,350 --> 00:13:30,789
l tried to bring the sense of me
that meets up with the character.

223
00:13:30,950 --> 00:13:34,306
And George's journey is one...

224
00:13:34,470 --> 00:13:40,067
... that goes from optimistic youth
looking to the promise of the future...

225
00:13:40,230 --> 00:13:44,382
... to one that grows
into disillusionment...

226
00:13:44,550 --> 00:13:47,110
... and pain...

227
00:13:47,270 --> 00:13:52,981
... and the suffering
that goes with fighting for a cause...

228
00:13:53,190 --> 00:13:56,227
... that you believe in
but carries with it a tremendous price.

229
00:13:56,390 --> 00:13:57,823
l fell in love with him as a person.

230
00:13:57,990 --> 00:14:02,427
And his ease, his James Bond
kind of, you know...

231
00:14:02,950 --> 00:14:06,260
... handsome and cool and... .

232
00:14:06,670 --> 00:14:10,185
ln many ways, l wanted to be him
because he was just so cool...

233
00:14:10,350 --> 00:14:12,659
... and just had so much class
and, you know...

